%%TITLE
Viral load, physical status, and E6/E7 mRNA expression of human papillomavirus in head and neck squamous cell carcinoma.
%%ABSTRACT
The purpose of this study was to determine prospectively both human papillomavirus (HPV) load and physical status in different types of head and neck squamous cell carcinoma (HNSCC).HPV DNA, E6/E7 mRNA expression, viral load, and physical status of 184 patients with HNSCC were examined simultaneously by polymerase chain reaction (PCR)-based methods.The HPV genome was detected in 54 HNSCC samples (29.3%), particularly in tonsillar carcinomas (69.6%). Compared with nonoropharyngeal HNSCC, oropharyngeal carcinoma harbored a relatively higher viral load, especially in tonsillar carcinoma. Although integrated or mixed status was observed in 75.6% of HPV-16-positive samples, E6/E7 mRNA transcripts were detected in only 27.5% of HPV DNA-positive cases. High HPV-16 load correlated significantly with E6/E7 mRNA expression.E6/E7 mRNA expression in patients with HNSCC with low viral load remains low even in cases of integration to the host genome. Tonsillar carcinomas were significantly associated with HPV among various types of HNSCC.
%%MATERIALS AND METHODS
Study population and specimens
We examined 184 biopsy or surgical excision speci- mens of HNSCC diagnosed in the Department of Otorhi- nolaryngology, Head and Neck Surgery, at the University of the Ryukyus, Japan, between December 2006 and August 2010. Classification of the TNM stage was performed according to the American Joint Committee on Cancer (sixth edition, 2002), and samples were differenti- ated into grades according to the World Health Organiza- tion International Histological Classification of Tumors.22 The prevalence of HPV DNA was also determined in ton- sils resected from 47 control patients (age, 18 years) who underwent tonsillectomy for chronic tonsillitis during the same period. After approval of the research protocol by the Institutional Review Board of the University of the Ryukyus, informed consent was obtained for molecular analysis of the specimens from all patients with HNSCC and controls. Tissue samples were snap-frozen in liquid nitrogen during biopsy or surgical excision and stored in liquid nitrogen until further analysis.
Cell lines
A CaSki cell line (ECACC, Salisbury, Wiltshire, UK) was used as a control for amplification of the E2 and E6 genes. CaSki cells are considered to contain 600 copies of HPV-16 integrated into head-to-tail tandem repeats.23 A SiHa cell line (ATCC, Tokyo, Japan) was used as a control for HPV-DNA integration into the host genome DNA. SiHa cells contain 1 to 2 copies of HPV-16 inte- grated into chromosome 13q14-32,24 in which the E2 gene is disrupted but the E6 gene is retained.
DNA extraction
DNA was extracted from the samples, SiHa cells, and CaSki cells using the Gentra Purification Tissue kit (Qia- gen, Germantown, MD) according to the manufacturer’s protocol.
Polymerase chain reaction for detection of high-risk and low-risk human papillomavirus DNA
The presence and integrity of the DNA in all samples was verified by PCR b-globin gene amplification using the primers PC04 and GH20.25 Water (negative control) and DNA of HPV–16-positive CaSki cells (positive con- trol) were included in each amplification series. The presence of high-risk and low-risk HPV DNA was ana- lyzed by PCR using the general consensus primer sets
GP5þ/GP6þ and MY09/11.26,27 DNA samples that were
negative in the GP5 /GP6 or MY09/11 PCR were reamplified in an auto-nested PCR using the GP5 / GP6 primer pair as previously described,28 which can increase the sensitivity of HPV-16 detection up to 2.85 copies/ll. PCR was performed in a programmable ther- mal cycler (Veriti 96-Well Thermal Cycler, Applied Biosystems, Carlsbad, CA). Positive PCR products were purified and directly sequenced with an ABI PRISM 3130xl Genetic Analyzer (Applied Biosystems). Obtained sequences were aligned and compared with those of known HPV types in the GenBank database using the BLAST program.
Analysis of viral DNA load and physical status of human papillomavirus-16 by quantitative real-time polymerase chain reaction
To estimate viral DNA load and to evaluate the physi- cal status of HPV-16, quantitative real-time PCR was per- formed with the ABI Prism 7300 Sequence Detection System (Applied Biosystems) and TaqMan PCR Master Mix II (Roche Molecular Systems, Foster City, CA). Pri- mers and TaqMan probes that target the HPV-16 E6 and E2 open reading frames, as previously described, were used.9 Both the E6 and E2 probes were labeled with
FAM at the 50 end and with TAMRA at the 30 end (Applied Biosystems Japan, Tokyo, Japan). E2 primers
and probes recognize the E2 hinge region, which was deleted on HPV-16 integration. Amplification conditions were: 2 minutes at 50 C, 10 minutes at 95 C, and a 2- step cycle of 95 C for 15 seconds and 60 C for 60 sec- onds for a total of 50 cycles.9 For specificity and validity testing, DNA from the CaSki and SiHa cell lines were examined as positive controls for intact E2 and E6 genes and for deleted E2 genes, respectively. Two standard curves for the E6 and E2 genes were generated by ampli- fication of serial 10-fold dilutions (101, 102, 103, 104, 105, and 106 viral copies) of a plasmid pB-actin carrying the complete HPV-16 early region (Addgene, Cambridge, MA). Viral DNA load was determined by calculation of E6 copy numbers.
For cellular DNA quantification, an external standard curve was generated using known serial dilutions (0.3, 3, 30, and 300 ng) of human genomic placental DNA (Sig- ma–Aldrich, St. Louis, MO),29 and b-globin was ampli- fied as described by van Duin et al.30 The amount of DNA (ng) was calculated by plotting the Ct values against the logarithm of the standard curve.
The physical status of HPV-16 was determined accord- ing to a previously described method.9 The total E6 copy number in 50 ng cellular DNA was determined, then the integrated E6 was calculated by subtracting the E2 copy number (episomal) from the total E6 copy number (episo- mal and integrated). Ratios of E2 copy number/total E6
of <1 indicate the presence of both integrated and episo- mal forms. The ratio of E2 to integrated E6 represents the
amount of the episomal form in relation to the integrated form. An E2/E6 ratio almost equal to 1 indicates the pre- dominance of the episomal form, whereas a ratio of 0 indicates the presence of only the integrated form.9
Total RNA extraction and detection of high-risk human papillomavirus E6/E7 mRNA transcripts by
Total RNA was isolated from 5 to 10 mg frozen sam- ples of HPV DNA-positive tumors, SiHa cells, and CaSki

cells using the ToTALLY RNA kit (Ambion, Austin, TX) according to the manufacturer’s instructions, and sus- pended in 50 lL ultra high-quality diethyl pyrocarbonate- treated water. Before cDNA synthesis, any residual DNA was removed through incubation with 1 U DNase I (Ambion) at room temperature for 25 minutes. cDNA was then synthesized from DNA-free total RNA using the RETROscript Kit (Ambion) according to the manufac- turer’s instructions. To examine the presence of contami- nating DNA in RNA samples, all the assays were per- formed both with and without reverse transcriptase.
To detect high-risk E6/E7 mRNA transcripts, PCR was performed with the cDNA of HPV DNA-positive samples using the TaKaRa PCR Human Papillomavirus Typing Set (Takara Bio, Otsu, Shiga, Japan), which can identify high-risk HPV types 16, 18, 31, 33, 35, 52, and 58. Posi- tive PCR products were purified and directly sequenced.
To verify the HPV-16 E6/E7 mRNA transcripts, the HPV-16 DNA-positive samples were also examined using a half-nested PCR approach with cDNA, as previously described by Wiest et al.31 Primers used for PCR were as follows: E6 forward, 50-AATGTTTCAGGACCCA-
CAGG-30; E7 forward, 50-TGAAATAGATGGTC-
CAGCTGG-30; and E7 reverse, 50-TGCCCATTAA-
CAGGTCTTCC-30. Because the primers E6 forward and
E7 reverse were used for the first PCR, amplicons of
unspliced E6/E7 mRNA and E6*I and E6*II (2 splice variants of E6/E7 mRNA) were expected at the respective sizes of 715 bp, 533 bp, and 416 bp. Subsequently, E7 forward and E7 reverse were used for a half-nested PCR, and 149-bp PCR products were expected to be yielded for a positive specimen. Positive PCR products were puri- fied and directly sequenced with an ABI PRISM 3130xl Genetic Analyzer (Applied Biosystems).
Statistical analysis
A 2-tailed Pearson chi-square test or Fisher exact test was performed to determine the difference between HPV prevalence in HNSCC and control samples, the associa- tion between clinical characteristics and HPV status, and the association between HPV DNA load and expression of mRNA. The same test was also used to compare the differences of incidence of high-risk HPV DNA and E6/ E7 mRNA transcripts between tonsillar SCC and non ton- sillar HNSCC. Relationships between HPV status and clinicopathological parameters (sex, age, tobacco con- sumption, alcohol consumption, TNM stage, degree of differentiation, and origin of cancer) were analyzed by cross-tabulation and logistic regression modeling. Odds ratios (ORs) with 95% confidence intervals (CIs) and 2- tailed p values were calculated. A Mann–Whitney U test was used to determine the difference between viral load in oropharyngeal and nonoropharyngeal HNSCC. For all statistical analyses, statistical significance was established
